\pagebreakNum
### A Cloud Serpent's Lair
While younger cloud serpents are known to be free-spirited wanderers, ancient cloud serpents usually stick to a single location, though their territory still encompasses several square miles.

#### Lair Actions
On initiative count 20 (losing initiative ties), the cloud serpent takes a lair action to cause one of the following effects; it can't use the same effect two rounds in a row:
- The cloud serpent causes a thick mist to blanket a 120-foot-radius sphere centered on a point within range. The sphere spreads around corners, and its area is heavily obscured. It lasts for 10 minutes or until a wind of moderate or greater speed (at least 10 miles per hour) disperses it. The cloud serpent can see through this mist.
- The cloud serpent changes the weather in the area, either causing a thunderstorm or calming one. Treat this as if the *control weather* spell had been cast, with the precipitation and wind stages increasing or decreasing by one step each on each of the cloud serpent's turns until it reaches stage 1 or stage 5. Once the stages are 4 or above, it is considered a thunderstorm. Extreme weather conditions are described on page 110 of the Dungeon Master's Guide.
- The cloud serpent covers itself in a sheath of protective wind. It is immune to all damage and effects but can take no offensive actions until its next lair action.
- The cloud serpent causes a strong gust of wind to burst froth from its body. This takes the form of either a 60-radius sphere centered on it or a 120 foot long by 15 foot wide line. Creatures in the area must make a DC 21 Strength save or be pushed 20 feet away from the cloud serpent.

#### Regional Effects
The territory of an ancient cloud serpent is changed by its inner storm, which creates on or more of the following effects:
- The air in a 6 mile radius crackles with static electricity. Large amounts of metal can invite lightning strikes.
- The cloud serpent can change the shape and color of clouds on a whim.
- An eternal thunderstorm rages in a 6 mile radius. Alternatively, the weather in the area is eternally peaceful.

If the cloud serpent dies, the effects fade over the course of 1d10 days.

\columnbreak

> ##### Variant: Heavenly Cloud Serpent
> A very rare few cloud serpents possess a deep connection to the spirits. These heavenly creatures have an inner white-gold light that shines through the gaps in their scales as well as their eyes, mouth, horns, and claws. They possess the following traits:
> ___
> - ***Illumination.*** A heavenly cloud serpent hatchling sheds bright light in a 5-foot radius and dim light an additional 5 feet. These ranges increases to 20 feet for a young cloud serpent, 30 feet for an adult cloud serpent, and to 60 feet for an ancient cloud serpent.
> - ***Aura of Peace and Hope.*** The cloud serpent and allied creatures within the area of the cloud serpent's bright illumination cannot be charmed or frightened as long as it is conscious.
> - ***Innate Spellcasting.*** A heavenly cloud serpent can cast certain spells innately. Their spellcasting ability is Charisma, and they gain innate spells at each age category: <br> **Hatchling.** At will: *dancing lights*. 1/day: *bless* <br> **Young.** 1/day: *aura of vitality*, *divine favor*, *lesser restoration* <br> **Adult.** 1/day: *aura of life*, *aura of purity* <br> **Ancient.** 1/day: *banishment*. 1/week: *raise dead*

> ##### Variant: Thundering Cloud Serpent
> Some cloud serpents manifest their inner storm earlier and more powerfully than other cloud serpents. These creatures crackle with lightning and have the ***Lightning Absorption*** and ***Static Skin*** traits. 
> 
> ***Lightning Absorption.*** Whenever the cloud serpent is subjected to lightning damage, it takes no damage and regains a number of Hit Points equal to the lightning damage dealt.
> 
> ***Static Skin.*** The cloud serpent deals an additional 3 (1d6) lightning damage with its melee attacks and creatures that hit the cloud serpent with a melee attack take 3 (1d6) lightning damage. The cloud serpent also has disadvantage on Stealth checks, except when in a thundercloud, where it has advantage instead.
> 
> A thundering cloud serpent has an altered Challenge Rating:
> ___
> - **Hatchling.** CR 1 (200 XP)
> - **Young.** CR 7 (2,900 XP)
> - **Adult.** CR 15 (13,000 XP)
> - **Ancient.** CR 20 (25,000 XP)
